Hey @CapriciousSage , 

We had some time to consider your proposal for SN0. For the folks unaware of the alternative proposal, it entails grabbing the emissions from Subnet 0 and placing them in a "community pool", where the senate (i.e. top 12 validators in the network) would be able to vote on whom gets funding according to their votes via a multi sig.

Unfortunately we believe the current structure is incomplete for the following reasons:

1)  the structure fails to nest itself sufficiently under competition. It cannot be enshrined in the code, and must be selected itself manually.

2) the structure overly concentrates power in the senate. In the proposal the senate is both the proposer of funding items, and the selector of those items. This is in contrast to subnets themselves where a balance of power is struct between miners (proposers) and validators (selectors) as disjoint groups. 

3)  It over centralizes power in the senate at the expense of the other 64 validators. Expanding this group would be necessary. 

Having said that, we (and I'm sure the community as well) are open to solutions that make use of subnets themselves and ensures full participation by tao holders, and not a select few ( possibly something akin to i.e. *idea/proposal mining.*). We believe this will solve the majority of the issues we have above. Meanwhile I’d love to hear everyone’s thoughts.

Larger validators certainly have more sway in ranking miners (thereby determining which models they run are more rewarded). The idea is all validators in a subnet are running the same reward models but scoring different responses from miners passed through those models. This creates different scores for the same miner (when WEIGHTS AREN'T COPIED) across the validator pool

Those scores are then compared to one another and used to reward validators. Validators straying from the herd to "choose their own model" (if they also ran miners for example) would be rewarded less tao if this does not match the scoring trend across all validators

Okay, this is super helpful -- it does help flesh out this from the "About" section: "...The unique innovation of [Yuma Consensus] is that it is agnostic to what is being measured, and allows for fuzzy consensus around probabilistic truths - truths like intelligence. Indeed, YC was essential for the validation of intelligence, given the nature of that amorphous information theoretic commodity."

Consensus is an effective tool against individual validators or even a "cabal" of validators going rogue and heavily deviating from the majority to reward their own miners but it does not do anything for copying weights. This is because the weights copied are calculated using an aggregate of weights from the largest validators. This is how a validator copying weights will be perceived as a more trusted actor (without validating or running a GPU btw) by the network than the largest validators themselves. This opens the door for a large group of validators to copy weights together and eventually begin introducing preferential scores for their own miners into the weights as the penalty normally associated with this behavior is mitigated by the total size/number of weight copiers.
